"61cfabc7-d7b3-3019-901f-60192cc7bc3e"	1	host: 	path:	width:	height:	duration:	mime_type: 	live: 	h264_profile: 	is_primary: 	lineNum: 0	0	attribution: 	description: "<p>These bite-size &quot;ice cream&quot; bonbons from Nom Nom Paleo might taste just like Ben & Jerry&#39;s Chunky Monkey ice cream but are actually made without using any milk or cream, dairy-based or otherwise. Their secret: frozen, pureed bananas! Watch the video to learn how to make these beautiful bonbons; they&#39;re bound to become one of your summertime freezer staples.<br />\n <p class=\"recipe-source\">Adapted from Nom Nom Paleo</p> Chunky Monkey &quot;Ice Cream&quot; Bonbons Ingredients<p>3 medium ripe bananas, peeled, sliced, and frozen<br />\n1 teaspoon vanilla paste or extract<br />\nPinch of salt<br />\n1/4 cup chocolate chunks, chopped<br />\n7 ounces dark chocolate candy melts<br />\n3 tablespoons chopped walnuts</p>\n Directions\nInto a food processor, blend frozen banana slices, vanilla, and salt until smooth and creamy.\nPut mixture into a container with a lid. Fold in chocolate chunks, cover, and freeze for at least 2 hours or until the banana ice cream is set.\nLine a baking sheet with parchment or wax paper. Use a melon baller or small cookie scoop to scoop out balls of frozen banana ice cream and place on the baking sheet. Cover tray, and place in freezer. Freeze overnight or until the scoops are set.\nIn a microwave-safe bowl, melt candy melts according to directions on the bag. Remove banana balls from the freezer, and using a skewer inserted into the ball or a chocolate dipping fork, dip in melted chocolate. Place chocolate-dipped bonbon back on the parchment-paper-lined baking sheet. While chocolate is still wet, sprinkle chopped walnuts on top. Store in freezer before serving.\n\n Information  Category Frozen, Desserts Yield 12-15 bonbons \n \n \n \n\n \n\n<a href='/node/35422192/print' target='_blank' title='Print recipe'>Print recipe</a> \n" "<a href=\"http://www.yumsugar.com/Banana-Ice-Cream-Bonbons-35355842\"><img width=\"1024\" height=\"1024\" src=\"https://sugarinc-a.akamaihd.net/files/2014/07/28/211/n/1922195/91835ab370f5393b_thumb_temp_image10906271406606286.xxxlarge.jpg\"/></a><p>These bite-size &quot;ice cream&quot; bonbons from <a href=\"http://nomnompaleo.com/post/54917164353/chunky-monkey-ice-cream-bon-bons\" target=\"_blank\">Nom Nom Paleo</a> might taste just like <a href=\"http://www.benjerry.com/flavors/chunky-monkey-ice-cream\" target=\"_blank\">Ben & Jerry&#39;s Chunky Monkey ice cream</a> but are actually made without using any milk or cream, dairy-based or otherwise. Their secret: frozen, pureed bananas! Watch the video to learn how to make these beautiful bonbons; they&#39;re bound to become one of your summertime freezer staples.<br />\n<div class=\"recipe-card\"><div class=\"recipe-logo\"></div> <p class=\"recipe-source\"><span>Adapted from <a href=\"http://nomnompaleo.com/post/54917164353/chunky-monkey-ice-cream-bon-bons\">Nom Nom Paleo</a></span></p> <h2 class=\"recipe-title\"><span>Chunky Monkey &quot;Ice Cream&quot; Bonbons</span></h2> <h3 class=\"recipe-section-title\">Ingredients</h3><p><span>3 medium ripe bananas, peeled, sliced, and frozen</span><br /><span>\n1 teaspoon vanilla paste or extract</span><br /><span>\nPinch of salt</span><br /><span>\n1/4 cup chocolate chunks, chopped</span><br /><span>\n7 ounces dark chocolate candy melts</span><br /><span>\n3 tablespoons chopped walnuts</span></p>\n <h3 class=\"recipe-section-title\">Directions</h3><div><ol>\n<li>Into a food processor, blend frozen banana slices, vanilla, and salt until smooth and creamy.</li>\n<li>Put mixture into a container with a lid. Fold in chocolate chunks, cover, and freeze for at least 2 hours or until the banana ice cream is set.</li>\n<li>Line a baking sheet with parchment or wax paper. Use a melon baller or <a href=\"http://api.shopstyle.com/action/apiVisitRetailer?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2Fgp%2Fproduct%2FB00004UE83%2Fref%3Das_li_tl%3Fie%3DUTF8%26camp%3D1789%26creative%3D390957%26creativeASIN%3DB00004UE83%26linkCode%3Das2%26tag%3Dpopsho-20%26linkId%3DJ7MNJ7TFSBF54QU2\" target=\"_blank\">small cookie scoop</a> to scoop out balls of frozen banana ice cream and place on the baking sheet. Cover tray, and place in freezer. Freeze overnight or until the scoops are set.</li>\n<li>In a microwave-safe bowl, melt candy melts according to directions on the bag. Remove banana balls from the freezer, and using a skewer inserted into the ball or a <a href=\"http://api.shopstyle.com/action/apiVisitRetailer?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2Fgp%2Fproduct%2FB0000E2OF1%2Fref%3Das_li_tl%3Fie%3DUTF8%26camp%3D1789%26creative%3D390957%26creativeASIN%3DB0000E2OF1%26linkCode%3Das2%26tag%3Dpopsho-20%26linkId%3DBQIQTNYZWC6RSAWZ\" target=\"_blank\">chocolate dipping fork</a>, dip in melted chocolate. Place chocolate-dipped bonbon back on the parchment-paper-lined baking sheet. While chocolate is still wet, sprinkle chopped walnuts on top. Store in freezer before serving.</li>\n</ol>\n</div><!-- .recipe-section-directions --> <h3 class=\"recipe-section-title\">Information</h3> <dl class=\"recipe-section-array\"> <dt class=\"recipe-section-array-key\">Category</dt> <dd class=\"recipe-section-array-value\"><span>Frozen, Desserts</span></dd> <dt class=\"recipe-section-array-key\">Yield</dt> <dd class=\"recipe-section-array-value\"><span>12-15 bonbons</span></dd> </dl><table class=\"voting yum_vote\"><tr><td>\n \n \n \n<embed allowscriptaccess=\"never\" type=\"application/x-shockwave-flash\" width=\"210\" height=\"35\" name=\"voting\" align=\"\" pluginspage=\"http://www.macromedia.com/go/getflashplayer\"></embed>\n \n</td></tr></table>\n<a href='/node/35422192/print' target='_blank' title='Print recipe'><div class='print-recipe'>Print recipe</div></a></div> \n"	title: 	genre: 	embed_right: 	duration: 	url: 	thumbnail: 	create_date: 	provider: 	thumbnail_dimensions:	credits: 	provisioning_source: 	show_name:	age_gate:	lineNum:31282	1	0	1	0	0	0	0	31282

"d219f234-47c5-3f9c-8d6c-9e9e4f83f67a"	1	host: 	path:	width:	height:	duration:	mime_type: 	live: 	h264_profile: 	is_primary: 	lineNum: 0	0	attribution: 	description: "In this send-up of \"Jeopardy,\" the twist is \"Black Jeopardy,\" hosted by \"Alex Treblack\" (played by Kenan Thompson, who was also one of the writers of the sketch).\n\nLouis C.K. plays the only white guy on the show and is clearly out of his element. He's \"Mark,\" an African American studies professor who immediately realizes his mistake when instead of history, the category choices include \"It's Been a Minute,\" \"That Girl,\" and \"Psssh!\"\n\nAt one point, the professor jumps in to take the clue \"It's been a minute since he got a job.\" His guess: \"Who is unemployed fellow? Black?\" He's met with scandalous looks from the other contestants, played by Jay Pharoah and Sasheer Zamata. \"Wrong answer,\" he says.\n\nThe skit inspired lots of comments on the Web. Viewer Steven Melton (@meltonstvn) raved on Twitter,\n\"The 'Black Jeopardy' skit on this weeks SNL was gold.\"\n\nFormer \"Saturday Night Live\" head writer Seth Myers (@SethMeyers) tweeted, \"'Black Jeopardy' is just a wonderful piece of sketch writing.\"\n\nThe Wrap praised the sketch as \"brilliantly irreverent.\"\n\nSlate called out the moment as one of the highlights of the show's \"absurdist and sometimes awkward sketches.\"\n\nSelf-mocking, odd, cringe-worthy: For Louis C.K. fans, that's a recipe for success.\n\nThis skit comes after \"Saturday Night Live\" faced criticism for its lack of cast diversity. Thompson stirred debate when he told TV Guide last year that the problem was finding qualified black female comedians. \"Like in auditions, they just never find ones that are ready,\" he said. "8bf484fc-20a2-38aa-a3be-00674038d493"	1	host: 	path:"8bf484fc-20a2-38aa-a3be-00674038d493.m3u8lang=en-USregion=US" "8bf484fc-20a2-38aa-a3be-00674038d493.m3u8lang=en-USregion=USsite=ivy"	width:	height:	duration:	mime_type: 	live: 	h264_profile: 	is_primary: 	lineNum: 5162	0	attribution: 	description: "Adrian (Patrick Swayze) and Barney (Chris Farley) leave the judges an almost impossible choice." "Chris Farley was only 33 when he died from a drug overdose in 1997. His hilarious performances continue to entertain. One of the comic's most memorable skits occurred early in his \"SNL\" career, in 1990: A Chippendales audition that pits the 300-pounder against hardbody Patrick Swayze. The two couldn't look more different as they strut their stuff onstage. The performance leave the judges torn; they tell Farley and Swayze, \"Either of you would make a wonderful addition to the Chippendale family.\" In the end, they go with Swayze because Farley is \"fat and flabby.\" Even though Swayze is weeping with joy, he can't help but praise his competitor: \"He's got some of the sexiest moves I've ever seen! And if you're really serious about going with me, it can only be because his body's so bad!\" The fellow cast members also couldn't believe their eyes. \"I played one of the judges and my experience was the same as anyone who's seen it on television,\" Kevin Nealon recalled in Tanner Colby’s biography \"The Chris Farley Show.\" He added, \"I can't think of the word to describe it. Incredulous, maybe? I did everything I could to keep a straight face.\" Mike Myers, who also played a judge, added, \"I knew in rehearsal a star was born.\" Some thought the joke came at too high a price, highlighting Farley's insecurities that fed his battle with addiction. \"'Chippendales' was a weird sketch. I always hated it,\" comedian Chris Rock said in the Farley biography. \"The joke of it is, basically, 'We can't hire you because you're fat.' There's no comic twist to it. It's just f***ing mean. A more mentally together Chris Farley wouldn't have done it, but Chris wanted so much to be liked. As funny as that sketch was ... it's one of the things that killed him.\" Comedian Jeff Garlin agreed that there was more to Farley than fat jokes. \"Chris Farley would have still been funny had he weighed 190 pounds and he didn't drink and he didn't smoke and he didn't do anything that was bad for him,\" he said. \"The sad thing is he didn't believe that, and he didn't know that.\" Despite such criticisms, the sketch is often praised as a classic — and Rolling Stone recently named it one of the funniest of all time. – By Claudine Zap (@zapkidd)"	title: 	genre: 	embed_right: 	duration: 	url: 	thumbnail: 	create_date: 	provider: 	thumbnail_dimensions:	credits: 	provisioning_source: 	show_name:	age_gate:	lineNum:5162	1	1	1	0	0	0	0	5162

The recipe is a great way to use leftover fish and makes a quick and easy lunch or light dinner option.<br />\n <p class=\"recipe-source\">From Ingrid Nilsen, Missglamorazzi</p> Salmon-Stuffed Avocados Ingredients<p>2 cups (16 ounces) salmon fillet, cooked and cooled<br />\n1/4 onion, finely chopped<br />\n2 tablespoons fresh dill, plus more to taste and for garnish<br />\n2-3 tablespoons Majestic Original Garlic Spread<br />\n1 lemon<br />\n2 ripe avocados </p>\n Directions\nIn a bowl, break up cooked salmon with a fork. Mix in onions, dill, and garlic spread, tasting and adjusting ingredients as needed. Squeeze 1/2 lemon juice and combine. The mixture should resemble tuna salad.\nCut avocados in half, remove pits, and scoop salmon mixture into the avocado halves. Garnish with lemon slices and more dill.\n Information  Category Main Dishes Yield Serves 4 \n \n \n \n\n \n\n<a href='/node/35406408/print' target='_blank' title='Print recipe'>Print recipe</a> \n" "<a href=\"http://www.yumsugar.com/Salmon-Stuffed-Avocado-Recipe-35404083\"><img width=\"1024\" height=\"1024\" src=\"https://sugarinc-a.akamaihd.net/files/2014/08/04/895/n/1922195/adbd70a35d1c9948_thumb_temp_image143725501407183336.xxxlarge.jpg\"/></a><p>On today&#39;s episode of Ingrid Dishes, Ingrid Nilsen (aka YouTube personality <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/user/missglamorazzi\" target=\"_blank\">Missglamorazzi</a>) is hacking <a href=\"http://www.lemonadela.com\" target=\"_blank\">Lemonade</a>&#39;s salmon-stuffed avocados. The recipe is a great way to use leftover fish and makes a quick and easy lunch or light dinner option.<br />\n<div class=\"recipe-card\"><div class=\"recipe-logo\"></div> <p class=\"recipe-source\"><span>From Ingrid Nilsen, <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/user/missglamorazzi\">Missglamorazzi</a></span></p> <h2 class=\"recipe-title\"><span>Salmon-Stuffed Avocados</span></h2> <h3 class=\"recipe-section-title\">Ingredients</h3><p><span>2 cups (16 ounces) salmon fillet, cooked and cooled</span><br /><span>\n1/4 onion, finely chopped</span><br /><span>\n2 tablespoons fresh dill, plus more to taste and for garnish</span><br /><span>\n2-3 tablespoons <a href=\"https://majesticgarlic.com/product/healthy-creamy-garlic-original\" target=\"_blank\">Majestic Original Garlic Spread</a></span><br /><span>\n1 lemon</span><br /><span>\n2 ripe avocados </span></p>\n <h3 class=\"recipe-section-title\">Directions</h3><div><ol>\n<li>In a bowl, break up cooked salmon with a fork. Mix in onions, dill, and garlic spread, tasting and adjusting ingredients as needed. Squeeze 1/2 lemon juice and combine. The mixture should resemble tuna salad.</li>\n<li>Cut avocados in half, remove pits, and scoop salmon mixture into the avocado halves. Garnish with lemon slices and more dill.</li>\n</div><!-- .recipe-section-directions --> <h3 class=\"recipe-section-title\">Information</h3> <dl class=\"recipe-section-array\"> <dt class=\"recipe-section-array-key\">Category</dt> <dd class=\"recipe-section-array-value\"><span>Main Dishes</span></dd> <dt class=\"recipe-section-array-key\">Yield</dt> <dd class=\"recipe-section-array-value\"><span>Serves 4</span></dd> </dl><table class=\"voting yum_vote\"><tr><td>\n \n \n \n<embed allowscriptaccess=\"never\" type=\"application/x-shockwave-flash\" width=\"210\" height=\"35\" name=\"voting\" align=\"\" pluginspage=\"http://www.macromedia.com/go/getflashplayer\"></embed>\n \n</td></tr></table>\n<a href='/node/35406408/print' target='_blank' title='Print recipe'><div class='print-recipe'>Print recipe</div></a></div> \n</ol>"	title: 	genre: 	embed_right: 	duration: 	url: 	thumbnail: 	create_date: 	provider: 	thumbnail_dimensions:	credits: 	provisioning_source: 	show_name:	age_gate:	lineNum:7478	2	0	2	0	0	0	0	14028

"1e150917-f4d0-3420-8c19-3fc66c3edcd8"	1	host: 	path:	width:	height:	duration:	mime_type: 	live: 	h264_profile: 	is_primary: 	lineNum: 0	0	attribution: 	description: "<p>When fast-food fans heard rumors that Frito-Lay and 7-Eleven were testing Doritos Loaded - essentially fried cheddar cheese sticks coated in Doritos crumbs - pictures of the snack went viral. As of July 2, the inside-out nachos will be available nationwide, but even if you can&#39;t make it to a 7-Eleven nearby, there&#39;s no need to shed a tear! We&#39;ve hacked a home take on these cheesy Doritos bites, so you can enjoy them anywhere (and anytime) in the US of A.</p>\n <p class=\"recipe-source\">From Nicole Iizuka, POPSUGAR Food</p> Cheese-Stuffed Doritos Notes <p><p>Before you start, check out these tips and tricks for safe deep-frying. </p>\n Ingredients<p>2 pounds medium cheddar cheese<br />\n1 1/2 cups Doritos Nacho Cheese chips<br />\n1 1/2 cups Doritos Spicy Nacho Cheese chips<br />\n1 teaspoon black pepper<br />\n1 teaspoon paprika<br />\n2 teaspoons garlic powder<br />\n4 eggs<br />\n1 1/2 cups all-purpose flour<br />\n1 quart vegetable, peanut, or canola oil</p>\n Directions\nSlice cheese into 1/2-inch-thick squares, and then slice each square on the diagonal to make 2 triangles.\nTo a food processor, add both Doritos flavors, black pepper, paprika, and garlic powder, and pulse until it resembles coarse breadcrumbs. Transfer to a shallow bowl.\nIn a separate, shallow bowl, beat eggs until whites and yolks are well combined. In a third shallow bowl, add flour. Set up a coating station: Set up cheese triangles to the farthest left-hand side, followed by flour bowl, followed by egg wash, followed by Doritos. Finally, line a cookie sheet with parchment paper, and set on the farthest right-hand side.\nTake each triangle of cheese, and coat in flour. Quickly dip into the egg wash, and then coat thoroughly in the Doritos crumbs. Lay onto a cookie sheet. Repeat with remaining triangles. Freeze the Doritos-coated cheese triangles for at least 3 hours before frying.\nWhen ready to serve, heat oil in a heavy-bottomed Dutch oven or electric deep fryer to 350°F. Working in batches, fry the cheese-stuffed Doritos for 1 to 2 minutes, or until the outside is crisp and golden brown.\nRemove the triangles from the oil with a slotted spoon, and place them on paper towels to drain. Serve immediately.\n\n Information  Category Finger Foods, Appetizers Yield 30 cheese-stuffed Doritos triangles \n \n \n \n\n \n\n<a href='/node/34157480/print' target='_blank' title='Print recipe'>Print recipe</a>" "<a href=\"http://www.yumsugar.com/Doritos-Loaded-Recipe-Hack-34166421\"><img width=\"1024\" height=\"1024\" src=\"https://sugarinc-a.akamaihd.net/files/2014/02/25/862/n/1922195/b70f9e3162a5654b_thumb_temp_image341664211393353293.jpg.xxxlarge.jpg\"/></a><p>When fast-food fans heard rumors that Frito-Lay and 7-Eleven were testing <a href=\"http://www.grubstreet.com/2014/02/doritios-loaded-seven-eleven.html\" target=\"_blank\">Doritos Loaded</a> - essentially fried cheddar cheese sticks coated in Doritos crumbs - pictures of the snack went viral. As of July 2, the inside-out nachos will be available nationwide, but even if you can&#39;t make it to a 7-Eleven nearby, there&#39;s no need to shed a tear! We&#39;ve hacked a home take on these cheesy Doritos bites, so you can enjoy them anywhere (and anytime) in the US of A.</p>\n<div class=\"recipe-card\"><div class=\"recipe-logo\"></div> <p class=\"recipe-source\"><span>From Nicole Iizuka, POPSUGAR Food</span></p> <h2 class=\"recipe-title\"><span>Cheese-Stuffed Doritos</span></h2> <h3 class=\"recipe-section-title\">Notes</h3> <p><p>Before you start, check out these <a href=\"http://www.yumsugar.com/How-Deep-Fry-Foods-Video-31329475\">tips and tricks for safe deep-frying</a>. </p>\n <h3 class=\"recipe-section-title\">Ingredients</h3><p><span>2 pounds medium cheddar cheese</span><br /><span>\n1 1/2 cups Doritos Nacho Cheese chips</span><br /><span>\n1 1/2 cups Doritos Spicy Nacho Cheese chips</span><br /><span>\n1 teaspoon black pepper</span><br /><span>\n1 teaspoon paprika</span><br /><span>\n2 teaspoons garlic powder</span><br /><span>\n4 eggs</span><br /><span>\n1 1/2 cups all-purpose flour</span><br /><span>\n1 quart vegetable, peanut, or canola oil</span></p>\n <h3 class=\"recipe-section-title\">Directions</h3><div><ol>\n<li>Slice cheese into 1/2-inch-thick squares, and then slice each square on the diagonal to make 2 triangles.</li>\n<li>To a food processor, add both Doritos flavors, black pepper, paprika, and garlic powder, and pulse until it resembles coarse breadcrumbs. Transfer to a shallow bowl.</li>\n<li>In a separate, shallow bowl, beat eggs until whites and yolks are well combined. In a third shallow bowl, add flour. Set up a coating station: Set up cheese triangles to the farthest left-hand side, followed by flour bowl, followed by egg wash, followed by Doritos. Finally, line a cookie sheet with parchment paper, and set on the farthest right-hand side.</li>\n<li>Take each triangle of cheese, and coat in flour. Quickly dip into the egg wash, and then coat thoroughly in the Doritos crumbs. Lay onto a cookie sheet. Repeat with remaining triangles. Freeze the Doritos-coated cheese triangles for at least 3 hours before frying.</li>\n<li>When ready to serve, heat oil in a heavy-bottomed Dutch oven or electric deep fryer to 350°F. Working in batches, fry the cheese-stuffed Doritos for 1 to 2 minutes, or until the outside is crisp and golden brown.</li>\n<li>Remove the triangles from the oil with a slotted spoon, and place them on paper towels to drain. Serve immediately.</li>\n</ol>\n</div><!-- .recipe-section-directions --> <h3 class=\"recipe-section-title\">Information</h3> <dl class=\"recipe-section-array\"> <dt class=\"recipe-section-array-key\">Category</dt> <dd class=\"recipe-section-array-value\"><span>Finger Foods, Appetizers</span></dd> <dt class=\"recipe-section-array-key\">Yield</dt> <dd class=\"recipe-section-array-value\"><span>30 cheese-stuffed Doritos triangles</span></dd> </dl><!-- 1.5 --><table class=\"voting yum_vote\"><tr><td>\n \n \n \n<embed allowscriptaccess=\"never\" type=\"application/x-shockwave-flash\" width=\"210\" height=\"35\" name=\"voting\" align=\"\" pluginspage=\"http://www.macromedia.com/go/getflashplayer\"></embed>\n \n</td></tr></table>\n<a href='/node/34157480/print' target='_blank' title='Print recipe'><div class='print-recipe'>Print recipe</div></a></div>"	title: 	genre: 	embed_right: 	duration: 	url: 	thumbnail: 	create_date: 	provider: 	thumbnail_dimensions:	credits: 	provisioning_source: 	show_name:	age_gate:	lineNum:8670	1	0	1	0	0	0	0	8670

"In 1977, Bill Murray was a rookie on \"Saturday Night Live\" -- a little-known 26-year-old who replaced fan favorite Chevy Chase.  Several episodes in, Murray sat in front of the camera to make an unusual apology: He wasn't good on the show, and he knew it. The three-minute confession to audiences was, ironically, funny. Funny because it was true. As Murray explained later: \"I'd been there a pretty long time, and they were sort of stuck with me. I'd actually had the idea to do something exactly like what it was, and that day when I went to work, Lorne said, 'You know, I think you should do a direct appeal.' He had the same idea too. So I did this thing, I wrote the thing, and it was kind of funny and I wasn't too full of myself or anything. There was a couple of tablespoons of humility in it. I got laughs in it, and I think the combination of the two broke some sort of ice, not just for me but for people watching.\" Bizarrely comical and brutally honest (he mentions his father's early death and his mother's struggle to raise nine children), it is an early glimpse of Murray's unique brand of humor. \"Bill Murray's Apology\" would prove to be one of countless nights he'd win audiences over."	title: 	genre: 	embed_right: 	duration: 	url: 	thumbnail: 	create_date: 	provider: 	thumbnail_dimensions:	credits: 	provisioning_source: 	show_name:	age_gate:	lineNum:14190	1	1	1	0	0	0	0	14190

"07301781-e18d-3b88-a08a-ac77be8707dc"	1	host: 	path:	width:	height:	duration:	mime_type: 	live: 	h264_profile: 	is_primary: 	lineNum: 0	0	attribution: 	description: "<p>This is easily the best fried chicken we&#39;ve ever sunk our teeth into. But would you expect anything less from Cédric Vongerichten, Perry St&#39;s chef de cuisine and the son of renowned chef Jean-Georges Vongerichten? Fried in an ethereally light batter that&#39;s bursting with flavor, this modern take on classic fried chicken is insanely delicious. Trust us when we say that you&#39;re going to love the tricks this chef has up his sleeve.<br />\n <p class=\"recipe-source\">From Cédric Vongerichten</p> Modern Fried Chicken Ingredients<p><b>For the spice mix</b>:<br />\n1 teaspoon kosher salt<br />\n2 teaspoons garlic powder<br />\n2 teaspoons onion powder<br />\n2 teaspoons espelette pepper<br />\n1 teaspoon allspice</p>\n<p>2 boneless, skin-on chicken breasts<br />\nVegetable oil</p>\n<p><b>For the batter</b>:<br />\n1 cup water<br />\n1/4 cup ginger, chopped<br />\n1 teaspoon sichuan peppercorn<br />\n1/2 teaspoon red thai chili<br />\n1/4 cup all-purpose flour</p>\n<p><b>For the chicken</b>:<br />\nAll-purpose flour for dredging<br />\nVegetable, peanut, or other high-smoke-point oil for frying<br />\nKosher salt<br />\nFreshly ground black pepper<br />\nFreshly grated lemon zest</p>\n Directions\nSeason chicken with salt, garlic powder, onion powder, espelette pepper, and allspice.\nHeat sauté pan until smoking hot, and coat the bottom with vegetable oil. Cook the chicken, skin side down only, until golden and fully crisped but only cooked at 80 percent.\nAdd water, ginger, sichuan peppercorn, and red thai chili to a blender and purée until smooth. Transfer to a bowl, and whisk in flour. Pass mixture through a chinois. Load batter into a siphon, and charge with 5 CO2 cartridges.\nPreheat oil to 375°F.\nDredge cooked chicken in all-purpose flour, quickly cover with aerated batter, and fry until golden brown, about 3-4 minutes.\nBlot dry over a paper towel, and season with salt, black pepper, and lemon zest. Serve immediately.\n\n Information  Category Main Dishes Cuisine North American Yield Serves 2 \n \n \n \n\n \n\n<a href='/node/35117061/print' target='_blank' title='Print recipe'>Print recipe</a> \n" "<a href=\"http://www.yumsugar.com/Fried-Chicken-Recipe-35210599\"><img width=\"1024\" height=\"1024\" src=\"https://sugarinc-a.akamaihd.net/files/2014/07/10/969/n/1922195/57e7cc176906049b_thumb_temp_image10906271405030314.xxxlarge.jpg\"/></a><p>This is easily the best fried chicken we&#39;ve ever sunk our teeth into. But would you expect anything less from Cédric Vongerichten, <a href=\"http://www.perrystrestaurant.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Perry St&#39;s</a> chef de cuisine and the son of renowned chef Jean-Georges Vongerichten? Fried in an ethereally light batter that&#39;s bursting with flavor, this modern take on classic fried chicken is insanely delicious. Trust us when we say that you&#39;re going to love the tricks this chef has up his sleeve.<br />\n<div class=\"recipe-card\"><div class=\"recipe-logo\"></div> <p class=\"recipe-source\"><span>From <a href=\"http://www.perrystrestaurant.com/#!/about-perry-street/c-dric-vongerichten/\">Cédric Vongerichten</a></span></p> <h2 class=\"recipe-title\"><span>Modern Fried Chicken</span></h2> <h3 class=\"recipe-section-title\">Ingredients</h3><p><span><b>For the spice mix</b>:</span><br /><span>\n1 teaspoon kosher salt</span><br /><span>\n2 teaspoons garlic powder</span><br /><span>\n2 teaspoons onion powder</span><br /><span>\n2 teaspoons espelette pepper</span><br /><span>\n1 teaspoon allspice</span></p>\n<p><span>2 boneless, skin-on chicken breasts</span><br /><span>\nVegetable oil</span></p>\n<p><span><b>For the batter</b>:</span><br /><span>\n1 cup water</span><br /><span>\n1/4 cup ginger, chopped</span><br /><span>\n1 teaspoon sichuan peppercorn</span><br /><span>\n1/2 teaspoon red thai chili</span><br /><span>\n1/4 cup all-purpose flour</span></p>\n<p><span><b>For the chicken</b>:</span><br /><span>\nAll-purpose flour for dredging</span><br /><span>\nVegetable, peanut, or other high-smoke-point oil for frying</span><br /><span>\nKosher salt</span><br /><span>\nFreshly ground black pepper</span><br /><span>\nFreshly grated lemon zest</span></p>\n <h3 class=\"recipe-section-title\">Directions</h3><div><ol>\n<li>Season chicken with salt, garlic powder, onion powder, espelette pepper, and allspice.</li>\n<li>Heat sauté pan until smoking hot, and coat the bottom with vegetable oil. Cook the chicken, skin side down only, until golden and fully crisped but only cooked at 80 percent.</li>\n<li>Add water, ginger, sichuan peppercorn, and red thai chili to a blender and purée until smooth. Transfer to a bowl, and whisk in flour. Pass mixture through a chinois. Load batter into a siphon, and charge with 5 CO2 cartridges.</li>\n<li>Preheat oil to 375°F.</li>\n<li>Dredge cooked chicken in all-purpose flour, quickly cover with aerated batter, and fry until golden brown, about 3-4 minutes.</li>\n<li>Blot dry over a paper towel, and season with salt, black pepper, and lemon zest. Serve immediately.</li>\n</ol>\n</div><!-- .recipe-section-directions --> <h3 class=\"recipe-section-title\">Information</h3> <dl class=\"recipe-section-array\"> <dt class=\"recipe-section-array-key\">Category</dt> <dd class=\"recipe-section-array-value\"><span>Main Dishes</span></dd> <dt class=\"recipe-section-array-key\">Cuisine</dt> <dd class=\"recipe-section-array-value\"><span>North American</span></dd> <dt class=\"recipe-section-array-key\">Yield</dt> <dd class=\"recipe-section-array-value\"><span>Serves 2</span></dd> </dl><table class=\"voting yum_vote\"><tr><td>\n \n \n \n<embed allowscriptaccess=\"never\" type=\"application/x-shockwave-flash\" width=\"210\" height=\"35\" name=\"voting\" align=\"\" pluginspage=\"http://www.macromedia.com/go/getflashplayer\"></embed>\n \n</td></tr></table>\n<a href='/node/35117061/print' target='_blank' title='Print recipe'><div class='print-recipe'>Print recipe</div></a></div> \n"	title: 	genre: 	embed_right: 	duration: 	url: 	thumbnail: 	create_date: 	provider: 	thumbnail_dimensions:	credits: 	provisioning_source: 	show_name:	age_gate:	lineNum:7670	1	0	1	0	0	0	0	7670

"d6b51ee8-d99f-3b13-a313-de7b6b1db04c"	1	host: 	path:"belolotusd0c447a3-721d-4704-842a-1b0f40f10c9c_d-EUw3BzW5MFBvoFkMftzA1rZnZPrJYM1Utjzwo0vq-hl3SATcitizAtEQFAdMWDZ7JavfqeVXM-_3_0b=2210m=video%2fmp4" "belolotusd0c447a3-721d-4704-842a-1b0f40f10c9c_d-EUw3BzW5MFBvoFkMftzA1rZnZPrJYM1Utjzwo0vq-hl3SATcitizAtEQFAdMWDZ7JavfqeVXM-_3_0.m3u8b=2210m=application%2fvnd.apple.mpegurl"	width:	height:	duration:	mime_type: "video/mp4" "application/vnd.apple.mpegurl"	live: 	h264_profile: 	is_primary: 	lineNum: 16166	0	attribution: 	description: "<p>TEMPE, Ariz. -- An experimental Ebola treatment with roots in Arizona may have saved the lives of two American aid workers infected while in Africa.<br />\n<br />\nZMapp was developed by San Diego-based Mapp Pharmaceutical and produced at Kentucky BioProcessing, but the drug is based on research conducted at Arizona State University.<br />\n<br />\nCharlie Arntzen, an ASU Regents&#39; professor and the founding director of the Biodesign Institute, has focused his work on plant-based vaccine delivery systems. And it turns out, tobacco plants seem to be perfect factories for pumping out Ebola antibodies.<br />\n<br />\nEbola-specific antibodies in plants were pioneered under a grant given to ASU by the U.S. Army Medical Research Institute of Infectious Diseases. According to ASU, the Army funded the development of the drug so that it could be stockpiled in the event of a natural outbreak or bioterrorism event.<br />\n<br />\nScientists from ASU and Mapp have been working together for 15 years.<br />\n<br />\nProducing the drug begins with exposing mice to fragments of the virus, generating Ebola-specific antibodies. The tobacco plants are then induced to replicate the antibodies.<br />\n<br />\n&quot;Most importantly, you need to have population of antibodies,&quot; said associate professor Qiang &quot;Shawn&quot; Chen.<br />\n<br />\nWithin a couple weeks of being modified, the plants are harvested, ground into liquid, purified and turned into tiny doses at Kentucky BioProcessing.<br />\n<br />\n&quot;These antibodies will bind to the Ebola virus to prevent them from either getting to other cells or, you know, basically immobilize them,&quot; Chen said.<br />\n<br />\nWith the infection of new cells blocked by the antibodies, the human immune system may be able to fight off the virus.<br />\n<br />\nThe drug has never been tested in humans, but a related plant-based vaccine tested in mice showed an 80 percent effectiveness against the Ebola virus, according to ASU.<br />\n<br />\nThe United States government allowed compassionate use of the experimental drug for Kent Brantly and Nancy Writebol, and there have been reports that the patients are improving.<br />\n<br />\nThe 2014 outbreak of Ebola in west Africa is the largest and longest in history.<br />\n<br />\nEbola is capable of producing viral hemorrhagic fever, shock and multiple organ failure often leading to death. It typically has a fatality rate of 90 percent.<br />\n<br />\nThe World Health Organization declared the outbreak an international public health emergency requiring an extraordinary response to stop the spread. <br />\n<br />\nChen said this research could lead to treatment for other diseases.<br />\n<br />\n&quot;Hopefully someday that will be developed into a drug which can treat patients who are exposed to West Nile virus,&quot; he said.</p>" "<p>TEMPE, Ariz. -- An experimental <a href=\"http://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/fs103/en/\" target=\"_blank\">Ebola</a> treatment with roots in Arizona may have saved the lives of two American aid workers infected while in Africa.<br />\n<br />\n<a href=\"http://www.biodesign.asu.edu/file/biodesign_ebola_8-2014.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">ZMapp</a> was developed by San Diego-based Mapp Pharmaceutical and produced at Kentucky BioProcessing, but the drug is based on research conducted at Arizona State University.<br />\n<br />\nCharlie Arntzen, an ASU Regents&#39; professor and the founding director of the <a href=\"http://www.biodesign.asu.edu\" target=\"_blank\">Biodesign Institute</a>, has focused his work on plant-based vaccine delivery systems. And it turns out, tobacco plants seem to be perfect factories for pumping out Ebola antibodies.<br />\n<br />\nEbola-specific antibodies in plants were pioneered under a grant given to ASU by the U.S. Army Medical Research Institute of Infectious Diseases. According to ASU, the Army funded the development of the drug so that it could be stockpiled in the event of a natural outbreak or bioterrorism event.<br />\n<br />\nScientists from ASU and Mapp have been working together for 15 years.<br />\n<br />\nProducing the drug begins with exposing mice to fragments of the virus, generating Ebola-specific antibodies. The tobacco plants are then induced to replicate the antibodies.<br />\n<br />\n&quot;Most importantly, you need to have population of antibodies,&quot; said associate professor Qiang &quot;Shawn&quot; Chen.<br />\n<br />\nWithin a couple weeks of being modified, the plants are harvested, ground into liquid, purified and turned into tiny doses at Kentucky BioProcessing.<br />\n<br />\n&quot;These antibodies will bind to the Ebola virus to prevent them from either getting to other cells or, you know, basically immobilize them,&quot; Chen said.<br />\n<br />\nWith the infection of new cells blocked by the antibodies, the human immune system may be able to fight off the virus.<br />\n<br />\nThe drug has never been tested in humans, but a related plant-based vaccine tested in mice showed an 80 percent effectiveness against the Ebola virus, according to ASU.<br />\n<br />\nThe United States government allowed compassionate use of the experimental drug for Kent Brantly and Nancy Writebol, and there have been reports that the patients are improving.<br />\n<br />\nThe 2014 outbreak of Ebola in west Africa is the largest and longest in history.<br />\n<br />\nEbola is capable of producing viral hemorrhagic fever, shock and multiple organ failure often leading to death. It typically has a fatality rate of 90 percent.<br />\n<br />\nThe World Health Organization declared the outbreak an international public health emergency requiring an extraordinary response to stop the spread. <br />\n<br />\nChen said this research could lead to treatment for other diseases.<br />\n<br />\n&quot;Hopefully someday that will be developed into a drug which can treat patients who are exposed to West Nile virus,&quot; he said.</p>"	title: 	genre: 	embed_right: 	duration: 	url: 	thumbnail: 	create_date: 	provider: 	thumbnail_dimensions:	credits: 	provisioning_source: 	show_name:	age_gate:	lineNum:16166	1	1	1	0	0	0	0	16166

(WHAS11) -- In this month&#39;s Buddy Check 11 we&#39;re talking about the importance of mammograms. They are the most common way to detect an early stage breast cancer.  The James Graham Brown Cancer Center&#39;s mobile mammography unit travels throughout Kentuckiana year-round and it is saving lives.<br />\n<br />\nPamela Frisk had been getting regular and healthy mammograms for years when she unexpectedly lost her job and her healthcare.  That&#39;s when she started going to a doctor at the Iroquois Family Health Center and first visited the mobile mammography unit.<br />\n<br />\nInside it holds a lot more than you might think -- a state-of-the-art digital mammogram imaging machine, a private dressing room and office area. For Pam, it held unexpected news.<br />\n<br />\n&quot;They called me and asked me to come back because they saw something,&quot; she remembers from her visit last fall.  That something turned out to be a rare and slow-moving breast cancer that had already spread to her lymph nodes.<br />\n<br />\n&quot;I was surprised,&quot; she said.  &quot;I was surprised because it doesn&#39;t run in my family.  That&#39;s what I wasn&#39;t expecting.&quot;<br />\n<br />\nThis moving unit can find a moving cancer fast. "ddabd865-9888-352f-91bf-6a0235af7b73"	2	host: 	path:	width:	height:	duration:	mime_type: 	live: 	h264_profile: 	is_primary: 	lineNum: 0	2	attribution: 	description: "Cat videos are one of the best things about the Internet. And Lil Bub is one of its biggest stars — an odd-looking yet totally adorable \"perma-kitten,\" famous for her big, green eyes, long pink tongue, and rumbling purr. Help Lil Bub's Big Fund by visiting <a class=\"\" target=\"\" href=\"http://lilbub.com/bigfund\">LIl Bub's Big Fund</a><br>\n\n<br>\n\nIn honor of Pet Week, we are featuring a playlist of animal videos — and Lil Bub leads the pack.\n<br>\n\n<br>\n\n    The furry feline is more than a memorable mug: The runt of a litter born in an Indiana toolshed in 2011, Lil Bub was rescued by Mike Bridavsky, who took her in after others declined to do so.\n\n<br>\n\n<br>\n\n    Even at eight weeks, it was clear the little kitty had some serious afflictions and would require a great deal of care.\n\n<br>\n\n<br>\n\n    Bub was born with multiple genetic mutations that add up to her one-of-a-kind look: Dwarfism gives her stubby legs and a long body, making movement difficult. She has an extra toe on each paw. Her teeth never grew in and her short lower jaw leaves her tongue hanging out.\n\n<br>\n\n<br>\n\n    Then there are those big, green eyes — and the noises she makes. \"Her sounds are absolutely bizarre,\" Bridavsky said. \"She doesn't sound like a cat.\"\n\n<br>\n\n<br>\n\n    The recording engineer already shares his house with four other cats, and didn't want another — but Lil Bub proved irresistible. \"I saw a picture and fell in love,\" Bridavsky told Yahoo Screen. \"I like things that are unique and special. And Bub is the epitome of all that.\"\n\n<br>\n\n<br>\n\n    After he posted photos of Lil Bub on his Tumblr blog, many others (including Oscar winner Whoopi Goldberg) fell for her as\nwell. The rest is Internet history: The feline fame resulted in a documentary, a book, a Web series, and a TV show. It's all to help a good cause: <a class=\"\" target=\"\" href=\"http://lilbub.com/bigfund\">LIl Bub's Big Fund</a>\n\n<br>\n\n<br>\n\n    In fact, everything Lil Bub does is to raise money and awareness for cats with special needs — Bridavsky calls her the \"poster child.\"\n\n<br>\n\n<br>\n\n    The video of Lil Bub at the park shows her running around and healthy, but it wasn't always that way. \"About a year ago she could barely move,\" said Bridavsky. \"It's kind of a miracle.\"\n\n<br>\n\n<br>\n\n    Next up, Lil Bub will be greeting up to 200 paying fans at the #Oaklandcatvidfest on May 10 — all to benefit charity.\n\n<br>\n\n<br>\n\n    \"We got interested in Lil Bub, because she was rescued by Mike,\" festival producer Issabella Shields told Yahoo Screen. \"She's just magical. Her little purr, her little squeak. She just radiates sweetness. You just don't get bored of watching her.\"\n\n<br>\n\n<br>\n\nHer fans would agree.\n\n<br>\n\n<br>\n\n— Claudine Zap (@zapkidd)" "Cat videos are one of the best things about the Internet.
